  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Roots can be traced back to efforts to combat organized crime in the early 20th century\n- Initial focus was on preventing criminal enterprises from concealing illicit proceeds\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - United States:\n- First comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs\n- Introduced international standards for criminalizing money laundering\n- Encouraged global cooperation in financial crime prevention\n\n4. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Establishment (1989):\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created comprehensive recommendations for national legal frameworks\n- Promoted global regulatory cooperation\n\n5. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US Annunzio-Wylie Anti-Money Laundering Act (1992)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - expanded AML regulations post-9/11\n\n6. Ongoing Evolution:\n- Continuous adaptation to emerging financial technologies\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency and digital transaction tracking",
